title._content: Republic of Texas $20.00 (twenty dollars) audited draft

description._content: Title: Republic of Texas $20.00 (twenty dollars) audited draft County of Origin: Harris County Town of Issue: Houston Currency Type: Audited Draft Denomination: $20.00 Bank Issuer: Republic of Texas Imprint: None Date Issued: May 27, 1837 Notes: This audited draft was issued in Houston by the Republic of Texas. Houston was established in 1836 to replace Harrisburg, which had been burned by Santa Anna. Named after Sam Houston, it was the seat of government from April 19, 1837, to January 18, 1840. Decorative designs border each edge of the note. The abbreviation ''No.'' is printed in the upper-left corner of the note; the number ''1940'' is handwritten adjacent to it. A dollar sign is printed in the upper-right corner; the amount ''20,00'' is handwritten adjacent to it. The note is signed on the recto by John Wyatt Moody, Auditor (TARO). Moody was the auditor for the Provisional Government of Texas and later for the Republic (TARO and Texas History Page). Signatures: J W Moody Auditor. Dimensions: 9.5 x 17.5 cm.
